<h1>Light Bulbs</h1>
<h2> About Light Bulbs:</h2>
<br>
<p>Light bulbs work by converting electrical energy into light.</p>
<ol>
    <li> <h3> Incandescent Bulbs </h3>
        <ul> 
            <li> When you turn on the switch, electricity flows through a thin wire filament inside the bulb</li>
            <li> The filament, usually made of tungsten, heats up due to the resistance it offers to the electric current</li>
            <li>As the filament gets hot, it starts to glow and emit light.</li>
            <li>The glass bulb around the filament prevents it from burning out quickly by keeping out oxygen.</li>

        </ul>
    </li>
    <h3>Compact Fluorescent Lamps (CLFs)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>When switched on, electricity passes through a gas (usually argon and mercury vapor) in a tube.</li>
        <li>This creates ultraviolet light, which isnt visible to the human eye.</li>
        <li>The Uv light hits the phosphor coating on the inside of the tube, which then glows and emits visible light.</li>

    </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
    <h3> Light Emitting Diodes</h3>
    <ul> 
        <li>LEDs are simicondoctor devices that emit light when an electric current passes through them.</li>
        <li>When the current flows, electrons and holes within the semiconductor recombine, releasing energy in form of photons (light).</li>
        <li>LEDs are highly efficent and produce very little heat compared to other types of bulbs.</li>
    </ul>
    </li>
</ol>
